# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1927-colored-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1920 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 51–19–2 record (45–15–2 in NNL games) and won the first NNL championship.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] Rube Foster was the team's owner and manager.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1920-chicago-american-giants-season] The team played its home games at Schorling Park in Chicago.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1921-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1921 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1920 baseball season.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1921-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 55–28–4 record (44–22–2 against NNL opponents) and won the NNL pennant.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1922-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1922 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1922 baseball season.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1922-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 46–30–1 record (38–23–1 in NNL games) and won the NNL pennant for the third consecutive season.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1923 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1923 baseball season.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 48–29–1 record (42–29 in NNL games) and finished in second place in the NNL.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The independent Cleveland Tate Stars returned to the NNL as an associate member to finish the Tigers' schedule.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1923-chicago-american-giants-season] The team was not considered a full member of the NNL.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1924 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1924 baseball season.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 55–27 record (52–27 in NNL games) and finished in second place in the NNL.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-chicago-american-giants-season] †Indianapolis dropped out of the league in June and was replaced by Memphis.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The **1924 Colored World Series** was a best-of-nine match-up between the Negro National League champion Kansas City Monarchs and the Eastern Colored League champion Hilldale.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] In a ten-game series, the Monarchs narrowly defeated Hilldale 5 games to 4, with one tie game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] It was the first World Series between the respective champions of the NNL and ECL.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] It was the second year of existence for the ECL, but no agreement could be reached in 1923 for a postseason series, owing primarily to unresolved disputes between the leagues.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Five members of the Baseball Hall of Fame participated in the series: Biz Mackey, Judy Johnson, and Louis Santop played for Hilldale, while Bullet Rogan and José Méndez played for the Monarchs.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Wilkinson was also inducted into the Hall.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Rogan pitched an 8-hitter, holding Hilldale scoreless until two out in the ninth.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Warfield's bases-loaded error in the sixth allowed the Monarchs to score two, and aided by Cockrell's three errors in the same inning, opened up a five-run inning for the Monarchs.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] , but instead used National League Park, home field of the Philadelphia Phillies, for the first two games, owing to its larger capacity.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Bill McCall could not get through the first inning, facing only three men and recording no outs before Bill "Plunk" Drake came in to relieve.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Hilldale led 9-0 by the end of the third.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] shut out the normally high-scoring Monarchs on four singles.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The Monarchs took a one-run lead into the bottom of the ninth and again into the bottom of the twelfth, but were unable to put Hilldale away.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] William Bell pitched 12 innings for no decision; he played the thirteenth inning in right field, as Rogan came in from center field to pitch the thirteenth inning.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Monarch fielding errors in the fifth and ninth innings allowed Hilldale to stay in the game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] received three intentional walks during the game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The game was called on account of darkness after thirteen innings.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] , on account of Pennsylvania's blue laws, which did not allow professional baseball games on Sundays.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] After yesterday's tie game, another game was rescheduled for the following day.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Before a sparse weekday crowd, former Monarch Rube Currie relieved Red Ryan with one out in the third and the Monarchs leading 3–0, and shut them out the rest of the game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Hilldale tied the game in the third on two base hits, a walk, and three steals, including Otto Briggs' steal of home.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Two walks and two errors helped score Hilldale's winning run with none out in the ninth.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] 's three-run inside-the-park home run with one out in the ninth shocked the crowd into silence and provided the difference in the game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] A controversial umpire call and three defensive misplays helped set the table for Johnson's heroics.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Until the fatal ninth, the game had been a classic pitchers' duel between staff aces Winters and Rogan.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Winters finished the game with a flourish, retiring 25 of the last 26 men he faced.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Rube Foster had originally scheduled games Five, Six and Seven for his own ballpark, but Kansas City ownership and fans strenuously objected to losing such lucrative dates, and Foster relented.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Phil Cockrell started the game for Hilldale, but was driven from the mound in the first inning, allowing four runs.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] pitched the remainder of the game, but tired in the eighth when the Monarchs scored the tie-breaking run.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Nip Winters pitched twelve innings and took the loss, while Méndez pitched brilliantly in relief for the win.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] stole home in the fourth inning to start the Monarchs' scoring.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Bullet Rogan did not hit the ball out of the infield, but still managed to get three hits, score one run, and drive in the winning tally in the twelfth inning.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] In one of Negro league baseball's legendary games, the Monarchs rallied for three runs in the ninth to stun Hilldale.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] foul popup, Duncan lined a single past Mackey that scored the tying and winning runs.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Also legendary was the vicious verbal assault that Warfield launched against Santop following the loss, laying blame for the loss squarely at Santop's feet.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Santop and others were already in tears in their locker room following the game, and it is one of Blackball's legends that Santop never recovered from the humiliation of Warfield's tirade.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Starting and completing his fourth game of the series, Nip Winters won for the third time to tie the series.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] William Bell started for Kansas City, but was shelled with none out in the fifth inning when Hilldale tied the score 2-2.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Drake pitched creditably until tiring in the ninth, when Hilldale scored two to win.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] The Series was now tied for the third time.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] He matched Hilldale starter Scrip Lee zero for zero for seven full innings until Lee tired in the bottom of the eighth.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] Lee changed from his normal submarine delivery to an overhand style in that inning, and the Monarchs scored five runs off of him, including one by Méndez himself.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1924-colored-world-series] When Hilldale went out in the ninth, the Monarchs had won the first Colored World Series.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1925-chicago-american-giants-season] The **1925 Chicago American Giants baseball team** represented the Chicago American Giants in the Negro National League (NNL) during the 1925 baseball season.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1925-chicago-american-giants-season] The team compiled a 57–43–2 record (52–42–2 in NNL games) and finished in fourth place in the NNL.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The **1927 Colored World Series** was the championship tournament for the 1927 season of Negro league baseball.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It was the fourth overall Series played.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It matched the Chicago American Giants, champions of the Negro National League (1920–1931) and the Bacharach Giants of Atlantic City, New Jersey, champions of the Eastern Colored League.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The Giants won the series five games to three (with one tie).
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The two teams had faced a year earlier in the 1926 Colored World Series with the same result.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] This time around, it was Chicago that had to hold back a comeback, since they had won the first four games (all played in Chicago) and needed just one more to clinch the Series.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] They proceeded to lose three of the next four while tying Game 6, which meant that there could have been a Game 10 if Chicago did not win in Atlantic City.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] They prevailed 11–4 in Game 9 to prevail and win their second straight title.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It was the last Negro World Series played for fifteen years.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] In Game 5, Luther Farrell of the Bacharach Giants pitched a shortened no-hitter, allowing no hits in a 7-inning complete game that was called early due to darkness.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] To get to the World Series, the Giants had to win the NNL Championship Series against the Birmingham Black Barons.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The Giants won Game 1 5-0 and Game 2 10–5 before dropping Game 3 6–5 to close out the Birmingham part of the Series.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] In Chicago, they won Game 4 6-4 and clinched the pennant with a 6–2 win on September 25.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] For Atlantic City, starter Luther Farrell pitched eight innings while allowing six runs on eight hits while walking one and striking out six and hitting two batters.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie "Bill" Foster allowed two runs on thirteen hits while walking two batters and striking out eight.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Atlantic City would use two pitchers for the game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Jesse Hubbard was pulled after pitching four innings and allowing nine runs on eleven hits while striking out one batter.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Hubert Lockhart pitched the remaining four innings while allowing two runs to score on three hits with one walk and three strikeouts.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie Powell allowed one run to score in nine innings while allowing four hits with three walks and five strikeouts.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Atlantic City would use three pitchers during the game in another rout loss.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Hubbard was used as the starter for the second straight game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He was replaced after allowing the first two baserunners to advance in the third inning (totaling four hits and four earned runs).
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Roy Roberts faced two batters and allowed the runners and one more to score on two hits.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Hubert Lockhart handled the remaining six innings, allowing two runs to score on four hits with one strikeout and on walk.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Meanwhile, George Harney threw a complete-game shutout, allowing just four hits while walking one batter and striking out eight.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Luther Farrell went eight innings and allowed nine runs to score on eleven hits with six walks and one strikeout, while Webster McDonald pitched nine innings and allowed one run on six hits while walking one and striking out four.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] To the derision of the Chicago teammates, the game was called after seven innings with Atlantic City winning.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] According to reports in the *Chicago Defender*, the team started to yell obscene gestures at the box seats where Postmaster Alford and the mayor were sitting.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie Foster pitched six innings and allowed three runs on five hits while walking three and striking out three.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Luther Farrell pitched a shortened no-hitter of seven innings while walking five and striking out three.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago scored in the fourth inning the basis of an error committed by Oliver Marcell that helped Steel Arm Davis get on base; he stole second and third base before Willie Jones committed an error that led Davis to score.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The second run scored in the fifth inning when Larry Brown walked and eventually reached home on an error committed by Cool Turner.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The game ended after ten innings due to darkness.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] This was the first Negro World Series game to have all the runs scored by each team to be composed entirely of home runs.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago starter Willie Powell went six innings and allowed one run on six hits while walking two batters and striking out four.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He was pulled for Eddie Miller, who pitched to one batter in the seventh inning (after Powell had allowed the first two runners to advance) before being pulled for George Harney.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He went 3+2⁄3 innings and allowed two hits, one walk, and two strikeouts.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] For Atlantic City, Hubert Lockhart pitched ten innings while allowing five hits and one run, walking two and striking out five.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Bacharach left nine runners on base (three times with two runners on) while Chicago left five.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] George Harney allowed eight runs on eleven hits in eight innings of work while walking five and striking out three.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Luther Farrell pitched a complete game while allowing one run on seven hits, six walks, four strikeouts, and two hit batsmen.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Webster McDonald started the game for Chicago, but he would only last four innings.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] In the fifth inning, he allowed a leadoff triple and two singles that tied the game (in total, he allowed eight hits with one walk and four strikeouts).
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Willie Foster was brought in to relieve him with a batter on first.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] An error would later bring the runner home.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago went from being up 4–2 to being down 5–4.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Foster would pitch four innings and allow two hits with one run while walking two and striking out one.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Jesse Hubbard pitched nine innings for Atlantic City, allowing five runs on six hits with four walks and four strikeouts.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The game turned in the eighth inning that inspired controversy as the 5–5 tie was broken.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] It started with a leadoff double by Clarence Smith, which was followed by a Willie Jones single (followed by a stolen base).
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Pinch hitter Ambrose Reid hit a flyball to center fielder Sanford Jackson.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The throw by Jackson was a long hard throw that went perfectly to catcher Jim Brown, who had the ball with him to block the plate.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Smith, trying to run home, ran outside the baseline and even ran into the shortstop on the play, but he eventually found a path to home plate and was deemed to have scored.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] The argument soon grew heated between the Chicago players and the umpires and fifteen Chicago police officers were brought to the field to restore the peace.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Brown was ejected and three position players switched positions.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago went down in the ninth inning and lost the game.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] Chicago starter Willie Powell pitched one inning and allowed a run to score with two walks and a strikeout before being pulled for Willie Foster.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He threw five innings while allowing three runs to score on eight hits and walking three with one strikeout before Rube Curry was brought in to save the eighth and ninth inning, and he pitched two perfect innings to close an 11–4 win.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] For Atlantic City, starter Hubert Lockhart pitched 1+2⁄3 innings and allowed five runs to score on three hits while walking four before being pulled for Luther Farrell.
[src:1927-colored-world-series/1927-colored-world-series] He pitched the remaining 6+2⁄3 innings and allowed six runs on 11 hits with one walk and nine strikeouts.
